<div id="review_3934345478" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3934345478" />
    <a title="Raechel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7540440-raechel"><img alt="Raechel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589511047p2/7540440.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3934345478?book_show_action=true">May 11, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Raechel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Raechel" href="/user/show/7540440-raechel">Raechel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6632450-streams-of-silver">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7540440-raechel?shelf=forgotten-realms">forgotten-realms</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7540440-raechel?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7540440-raechel?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7540440-raechel?shelf=the-legend-of-drizzt">the-legend-of-drizzt</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3934345478" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12429881275899214984">What a fun continuation of the Drizzt story!<br/><br/>Drizzt and co are on a quest to find the fabled Mithril Hall of Bruenor&apos;s childhood. Unknown to most of the group, an assassin is on their trail to find Regis.<br/><br/>There&apos;s not much I feel like I can say about this book. It&apos;s another fun D&amp;D adventure. I feel like it meanders a fair bit in the first third, like the DM is having trouble getting the party to follow the quest hook. Also in the first half of the book, I wasn&apos;t a fan of Catti-Brie, but I liked he</span>
  <span id="freeText12429881275899214984" style="display:none">What a fun continuation of the Drizzt story!<br /><br />Drizzt and co are on a quest to find the fabled Mithril Hall of Bruenor's childhood. Unknown to most of the group, an assassin is on their trail to find Regis.<br /><br />There's not much I feel like I can say about this book. It's another fun D&amp;D adventure. I feel like it meanders a fair bit in the first third, like the DM is having trouble getting the party to follow the quest hook. Also in the first half of the book, I wasn't a fan of Catti-Brie, but I liked her development in the second half. It feels like Salvatore realized she needed to be more than just a Sexy Lamp.<br /><br />There is still some 'D&amp;D Is For Teenage Boys' issues... the only named women are Catti-Brie (a sexy innocent), Whisper (a sexy double-crossing rogue), and Sydney (a non-sexy evil mage). Any other women mentioned are: an aggressive prostitute (which Regis <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[starts to hypnotize with his magic gem and it seemed like it was going to get rape-y, but they're interrupted <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>), the women that Wulfar's tribe rape (and Drizzt hopes Wulfgar's people will someday realize Women Are People Too), and... oh, a magic elf lady who is there to be Sexy and Helpful and flirt with Drizzt. Hey, maybe we'll see better progress in the next book?<br /><br />I like how the end of each book leads into the main quest for the next one. And I think it's really funny that there's been a <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[dragon fight <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> in each book. Is that going to be a theme?<br /><br />Besides the pointless first third of the book, I felt like the action scenes in this were very weird. Either the action is brushed over very quickly, so much so that a fight is just summarized in a couple sentences... or the action is described in such a weird way I honestly couldn't understand what exactly was happening. I'm going to assume Salvatore gets better at these as he continues to write dozens more Drizzt novels.<br /><br />I will still read the next book in this series, this is pretty predictable early D&amp;D adventure. Someone gets a magic weapon. They solve some ancient mystery (that's actually only 200 years old which honestly doesn't seem old AT ALL considering the lifetime of some races), and there's a plot hook for the next quest.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12429881275899214984" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


