    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_531229801" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/531229801" />
    <a title="Laura" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6183135-laura"><img alt="Laura" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1403902640p2/6183135.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/531229801?book_show_action=true">Feb 09, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura" href="/user/show/6183135-laura">Laura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6183135-laura?shelf=medieval-fantasy">medieval-fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6183135-laura?shelf=roleplaying-fodder">roleplaying-fodder</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer531229801" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8210120633664144203">In <i> Streams of Silver </i> Drizzt, Wulfgar, Bruenor and Regis head off in search of Bruenor&apos;s homeland, Mithril Hall, all the while being chased by a wizard hunting Drizzt who teams up with an assassin hunting Regis. This chase aside, their journey to the Halls themselves are filled with perils and trials that test their strength and endurance.<br/><br/>I enjoyed this book despite its shortcomings. There is plenty of action, even if you have to greatly suspend your disbelief--these characters are superheroes </span>
  <span id="freeText8210120633664144203" style="display:none">In <i> Streams of Silver </i> Drizzt, Wulfgar, Bruenor and Regis head off in search of Bruenor's homeland, Mithril Hall, all the while being chased by a wizard hunting Drizzt who teams up with an assassin hunting Regis. This chase aside, their journey to the Halls themselves are filled with perils and trials that test their strength and endurance.<br /><br />I enjoyed this book despite its shortcomings. There is plenty of action, even if you have to greatly suspend your disbelief--these characters are superheroes of the fantasy genre. They can fight through intense pain (broken ribs, sprained ankles), days of travelling, sleep deprivation, and survive without long-lasting damage. This, strangely, did not bother me so much because it reminded me of how fantasy games work. You are somehow better than the average Joe.<br /><br />However, as another review pointed out, there are hypocritical distinctions between good and evil. Entreri, the assassin, is distinctly placed on the "evil" side (and is compared to Drizzt's drow kin). Although he is most definitely a villain, to me he seems to be more of someone who enjoys doing what he's good at. How is he different from Drizzt and his friends, who slaughter orcs and tree creatures and gray dwarves without a blink of conscience? (N.B. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ Cattie-Brie kills a human and is momentarily upset over it. Just a few tears and it's supposed to be a huge loss of her innocence for killing someone who has a life outside of the battle.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Again, few characters see development. Regis does, as he did in the first book, and Cattie-Brie as well (to some degree). These books are action-driver rather than character driven. This is demonstrated in the <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ ridiculously stupid choice by Sydney to order Bok away from digging through the rubble covering Drizzt and Entreri. I mean COME ON! That was obviously done to convenience the plot, not because she truly thought it was a good decision.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. When reading this similar observation in another review, I was nodding my head furiously.<br /><br />Still, it was a good romp as any, although I am disappointed by the divisions between good/evil and people/monsters.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8210120633664144203" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

